# The spec is the contract

Each unit's steps, plus the invariant Rules in scope for it, define exactly
what its witnessing tests must verify -- no more, no less. The spec is
authoritative: do NOT re-derive intended behavior from the implementation.
Read the unit and take it as given.

The entire corpus under {{ corpus_root }} is READ-ONLY. Never edit, add, or
delete anything in it, under any circumstances. There is no exception. If a
spec unit itself looks wrong, see "# If the spec looks wrong" below.

# Witnessing tests

A test declares which units it verifies with the witnesses marker, using the
unit's coordinate:

  @pytest.mark.witnesses("authentication.fresh-code")
  def test_fresh_code_signs_in() -> None: ...

  @pytest.mark.witnesses("authentication.prefetch", partial="does not assert the code remains unspent")
  def test_login_page_redirects_via_script() -> None: ...

- partial= states precisely what the test does NOT cover; omit it when the
  test covers the unit fully.
- A test may carry several witnesses markers. Mark every unit the test
  genuinely witnesses -- including an in-scope Rule it partially verifies in
  passing (with an honest partial= note saying under which flow).

To find the current witnesses of your units, run the coverage matrix (one
JSONL record per unit, with its coverage and witnessing tests):

  uv run {{ specs_matrix_cmd }}

# The objective: converge each unit's witnesses to its scope

For every unit in your task, make its witnessing tests verify exactly the
unit's scope -- check BOTH directions:

- Coverage (forward): is every observable claim the unit's steps make
  actually verified by some witnessing test? If a step says an effect is
  observable (a code becomes spent, a redirect lands on "/"), a test must
  observe it. Add whatever verification is missing.

- Trace (backward): does every assertion in the witnessing tests trace back
  to one of the unit's steps or to an in-scope invariant? An assertion that
  traces to neither is gold-plating: it adds brittleness without verifying
  specified behavior. REMOVE it.

An unwitnessed unit (coverage "none") is not a special mode: it is simply
the farthest point from the fixed point, and the same objective applies --
create the witnessing test(s) that verify its scope, and record the work
under "CREATE_TEST".

A unit whose witnesses already verify exactly its scope needs no change:
leaving the changes object empty for it is a correct, good outcome, NOT a
failure. Do not add assertions merely to be thorough -- the unit's scope
fixes what "thorough" means.

Removing or simplifying an over-fitted assertion (or deleting a test whose
whole content is redundant coverage) is a real improvement, exactly as
valuable as adding a missing one -- record it under "IMPROVE_TEST".

Keep the witnesses markers honest as you work: set, clear, or reword every
touched test's partial= notes so they state exactly what remains uncovered.

# Witnessing invariant Rules directly

When your task's units include Rules (invariants), witness the property
itself, not just the flows scenarios happen to describe: write tests that
try to violate the property (present a spent code again, tamper with a
token, request user data without a session) and assert the system refuses.
An invariant quantified over all states and interleavings usually cannot be
fully witnessed by finitely many tests -- that is what honest partial= notes
and the PARTIAL_STEADY verdict are for.

# The verdict vocabulary

For every unit in your task, report a verdict -- its end state after your
work:

- "FULL": witnessing tests cover every observable claim; no partial= notes
  remain (or they were honestly cleared).
- "PARTIAL_STEADY": witnessed with partial= notes, and the uncovered residue
  named by those notes is untestable in kind -- universally quantified
  clauses ("under any interleaving of requests"), cross-installation
  properties, unobservable internals. This IS the fixed point for such a
  unit; future runs should not churn on it.
- "PARTIAL_IMPROVABLE": witnessed with partial= notes, but testable residue
  remains (you ran out of time, or the next step needs setup you lack).
  Honest unfinished work; future runs should re-target it.
- "NONE": still unwitnessed after this run (legitimate only together with a
  blocker or spec problem explaining why).

Residue that is merely expensive or slow to test is NOT steady -- claim
PARTIAL_STEADY only when no test of any kind could close the gap.

# If a witnessing test fails

You can record multiple kinds of changes -- they are not mutually exclusive
(one entry per kind, not per individual edit):

- "CREATE_TEST": write a new witnessing test for an unwitnessed unit.
- "IMPROVE_TEST": reshape existing witnesses to the unit's scope (add missing
  coverage, remove gold-plating, adjust partial= notes).
- "FIX_TEST": repair a witnessing test that fails although the implementation
  matches the spec.
- "FIX_IMPL": fix the program being tested.

Each change has a status: "SUCCEEDED", "FAILED" (tried but could not
complete), or "BLOCKED" (needs intervention beyond this task).

When deciding whether to fix the test or the implementation, the spec is the
arbiter: correct behavior is whatever the unit's steps and in-scope
invariants say it is. If the implementation diverges from the spec, fix the
implementation ("FIX_IMPL"); if a test asserts something the spec does not
say, fix the test.

# If the spec looks wrong

If a unit seems to specify the wrong behavior (contradicts another unit,
describes a flow that cannot exist, demands something clearly unintended),
do NOT edit the corpus and do NOT make the implementation match your own
judgment. Record the problem in that unit's "spec_problems" (with the edit
you would propose), set the status of the affected change to "BLOCKED", and
move on. Proposed spec edits reach a human through the report -- that is the
only channel by which the corpus ever changes.

