# Cross-cutting setup blockers

Some problems can only be fixed by a substantial, shared setup change that is
out of scope for a single task -- a missing shared fixture, or a dependency on
credentials or infrastructure absent from this environment. You see only one
spec file, so you cannot tell whether such setup is duplicated across the
suite, nor fix it suite-wide.
{% block infra_blockers %}{% endblock %}
When you hit one, do NOT paper over it with a brittle local hack. Instead:

1. Leave a comment at the relevant spot in the code, on its own line, in
   exactly this form so a later step can find it:

     # FIXME(tmr-specs): <one-line description of the shared setup change needed>

2. Record the blocker on the affected unit's "blockers" list, and set the
   relevant change's status to "BLOCKED" with an explanation in its
   summary_markdown.

A later integration step collects these, resolves the ones it can verify
suite-wide, and surfaces the rest to the user.

# Running the witnessing tests

Run exactly the witnessing tests you create or touch, by node id:

  uv run pytest <test_node_id> [<more_node_ids>...]{{ flags_suffix }}

Run them after each change (initial run, then after each fix attempt).
Before each run, decide on a brief description: "initial run" for the first
one, or something like "after adding the spent-code witness" for subsequent
runs. Record each run in the test_runs field of the outcome.

# Committing your changes

IMPORTANT: Each change kind MUST get its own separate commit. Changes of the
same kind should be combined in one commit. The commit message MUST start
with the kind in brackets, then name the coordinates it serves. Examples:

  [CREATE_TEST] authentication.fresh-code, authentication.used-code: witness the signin flows
  [IMPROVE_TEST] authentication.prefetch: remove assertion outside the unit's scope
  [FIX_IMPL] authentication.single-use-codes: refuse a spent code on the authenticate route

This means if you make both a CREATE_TEST and a FIX_IMPL change, you should
have exactly two commits. Do NOT mix different kinds in the same commit.

# Writing the result

Write the result atomically to avoid races with the orchestrator reading it:
1. First write to .test_output/{{ outcome_filename }}.draft (relative to the git repo root)
2. Then rename (mv) the .draft file to .test_output/{{ outcome_filename }}

The schema is:

{"changes": {"CREATE_TEST": {"status": "SUCCEEDED", "summary_markdown": "Witnessed both signin scenarios"}},
 "units": [
   {"coordinate": "authentication.fresh-code",
    "verdict": "FULL",
    "witnesses": [{"test": "apps/minds/imbue/minds/test_auth.py::test_fresh_code", "partial": null}],
    "blockers": [],
    "spec_problems": [],
    "summary_markdown": "Created a witness covering every step."},
   {"coordinate": "authentication.single-use-codes",
    "verdict": "PARTIAL_STEADY",
    "witnesses": [{"test": "apps/minds/imbue/minds/test_auth.py::test_spent_code", "partial": "does not exercise concurrent interleavings"}],
    "blockers": [],
    "spec_problems": [],
    "summary_markdown": "The interleaving quantifier is untestable in kind."}
 ],
 "errored": false,
 "tests_passing_before": null,
 "tests_passing_after": true,
 "summary_markdown": "Witnessed the signin file; all touched tests pass.",
 "test_runs": [
   {"run_name": "try_1", "description_markdown": "initial run"},
   {"run_name": "try_2", "description_markdown": "after adding the spent-code witness"}
 ]}

Fields:
- changes: object keyed by change kind (CREATE_TEST, IMPROVE_TEST, FIX_TEST,
  FIX_IMPL). Each value has status (SUCCEEDED, FAILED, BLOCKED) and
  summary_markdown. One entry per kind -- do not duplicate kinds.
- units: one entry per unit in your task, ALWAYS all of them (even untouched
  ones -- report their verdict as found). Each has coordinate, verdict (FULL,
  PARTIAL_STEADY, PARTIAL_IMPROVABLE, NONE), witnesses (objects with test --
  the pytest node id -- and partial -- the marker's note or null), blockers
  (strings), spec_problems (objects with problem and proposed_edit), and
  summary_markdown.
- errored: true only for infrastructure errors that prevented you from working.
- tests_passing_before: were the pre-existing witnessing tests passing before
  your changes? null when none existed.
- tests_passing_after: are all touched witnessing tests passing now?
- summary_markdown: overall markdown summary of what happened.
- test_runs: list of objects, one per test run, in order. Each has run_name
  and description_markdown.

